 `scalaClasspath` interacts with the `scala-compiler` dependency. It seems like it might be inferred from the classpath and potentially impacting the compile classpath by removing existing active classes that aren't referenced. Hmm, I should look deeper into how these dependencies are structured to ensure I'm getting it right. It’s important to understand the implications on the compilation process!\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Implemented focused coverage for `scala.concurrent.forkjoin.ForkJoinPool`.\n\nChanged:\n- Added dedicated test file:\n  - `tests/src/org.scala-lang/scala-library/2.11.8/src/test/scala/org_scala_lang/scala_library/ForkJoinPoolTest.scala`\n- Updated test configuration:\n  - `tests/src/org.scala-lang/scala-library/2.11.8/build.gradle`\n\nWhat the new test covers:\n- Configures Scala 2.11 `ForkJoinPool.commonPool` through its public system properties:\n  - `java.util.concurrent.ForkJoinPool.common.threadFactory`\n  - `java.util.concurrent.ForkJoinPool.common.exceptionHandler`\n- Ensures those properties are present before the pool initializes in JVM tests and native test runtime.\n- Triggers the common pool initialization path that performs:\n  - `ClassLoader.loadClass(...)`\n  - `Class.newInstance()`\n- Verifies the configured worker thread factory is actually used by executing bounded work on the common pool.\n\nI did not compile or run tests, per instruction.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_042447f617a89c220169f90cc4881481a09c9a0d05b7624ddf\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 770, "output": 1393, "cacheRead": 29184, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 31347, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1777929394823, "responseId": "resp_042447f617a89c220169f90cb3629481a0bf637bcc94bd96f6"}}
