[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating Gradle and Scala integration**\n\nI'm considering whether I need to use comments in my Gradle setup. There's a potential issue with not having `compileTestJava` in Gradle, but the `JavaCompile` class should be correctly imported as it's part of the defaults. I also wonder about the custom configuration, `scalaLibraryUnderTest`. \n\nAnother potential issue is the `compileTestScala` task possibly not recognizing Java classes, but it does see the output from `compileTestJava`. Since we only changed support class members to string constants, the Scala compiler might still verify referenced classes. I think it could be okay if I avoid Scala compiler reading the configured classes entirely.\n\n**Reviewing Gradle configurations and issues**\n\nI see that the `build.gradle` system property class names point to Java classes, which is fine. I need to ensure that `JavaCompile` resolves to version 2.11, despite potential Gradle conflicts. Creating a separate configuration could help avoid issues.\n\nIt's essential that the native runtime property classes are reachable in the native image, especially since the test class doesn’t reference `ForkJoinPoolConfiguredWorkerThreadFactory`. Also, I’m considering the requirement for `Class.newInstance()` which needs a zero-arg constructor, but since public classes have this implicitly, it should be okay. I need to check how the worker factory creation handles potential exceptions, especially with the parallelism.\n\n**Assessing JVM property settings**\n\nI need to remember that properties are set before the JVM starts, so there shouldn't be an issue there. However, if any other code in the same JVM initializes the common pool before my test, then the properties will be the same. The active class initialization executes with the first use, which means I have to ensure system properties are set beforehand to cover dynamic